ElementDescription: The NDAR Global Unique Identifier (GUID) for research subject
Subject ID how it's defined in lab/project
Date on which the interview/genetic test/sampling/imaging/biospecimen was completed. MM/DD/YYYY
Age in months at the time of the interview/test/sampling/imaging.
Notes: Age is rounded to chronological month. If the research participant is 15-days-old at time of interview, the appropriate value would be 0 months. If the participant is 16-days-old, the value would be 1 month.

ElementDescription: Sex of subject at birth
Notes: M = Male; F = Female; O=Other; NR = Not reported

ElementDescription: Visit name
Notes: e.g., Baseline, 6-Month Follow Up, Year 2

ElementDescription: The therapist set an agenda or established specific goals for the therapy session.
Notes: 1=Not at all typical of the session; 2=Slightly typical of the session; 3=Somewhat typical of the session; 4=Typical of the session; 5=Very typical of the session

ElementDescription: The therapist made connections between the client's current situation and his/her past.
Notes: 1=Not at all typical of the session; 2=Slightly typical of the session; 3=Somewhat typical of the session; 4=Typical of the session; 5=Very typical of the session

ElementDescription: The therapist worked to give the client hope or encouragement.

ElementDescription: The therapist repeated back to the client (paraphrased) the meaning of what the client was saying.

ElementDescription: The therapist encouraged the client to identify or label feelings that he/she had in or outside of the session.

ElementDescription: The therapist pointed out times when the client's behavior seemed inconsistent with what he/she was saying, like when he/she: suddenly shifted his/her moods or topics; was silent a long time; laughed, smiled, looked away, or was uncomfortable; avoided talking about specific topics or people.
